</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEB36D7FB74FF83C4ACF906FABDD0F4" blockId="21.[151,1437,1636,2035]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="B920EAC5FB74FF83C4ACF906FE14D1F0" bold="true" box="[199,510,1674,1699]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Characters of the species</emphasis>
. Male. Pronotum saddle-shaped, tegmina exceeding the 2nd or reaching the 3rd abdominal tergite, their apical external angle slightly less than 90°, rounded (
<figureCitation id="136F2A52FB74FF83C785F922FBB4D194" box="[1006,1118,1710,1735]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1574,1596]" captionText="FIGURE 16. Pronotum and tegmina of Peropyrrhicia maculata" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Figure 16</figureCitation>
). Fore femora unarmed, mid femora unarmed, hind femora with 4–6 outer and 3–5 inner black spines on ventral margins. 1st and 2nd antennal segment black below, others yellow with black rings at the base. Fore tibiae unarmed, mid tibiae with 4 spines on both margins of ventral side + 1 spur on each side, and 1 spur on outer dorsal side. Hind tibiae with 6 spines on ventral margins + 2 spurs on each side, and many spines + 1 spur on each side on dorsal margin. Appendage of 10th tergite widened towards the apex, which is more or less straight with acute lateral angles; at the base of the appendage is placed the 9th tergite, as one stout inflated extrusion, that ends with a flat apex (
<figureCitation id="136F2A52FB74FF83C0CFF803FAA0D0F4" box="[1188,1354,1935,1960]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 18" captionStart-1="FIGURE 19" captionStart-2="FIGURE 20" captionStart-3="FIGURE 21" captionStartId-0="23.[151,250,1966,1988]" captionStartId-1="24.[151,250,1709,1731]" captionStartId-2="25.[151,250,1898,1920]" captionStartId-3="26.[151,250,1615,1637]" captionTargetBox-0="[253,1327,342,1926]" captionTargetBox-1="[219,1357,198,1671]" captionTargetBox-2="[214,1406,187,1858]" captionTargetId-0="figure@23.[253,1327,339,1927]" captionTargetId-1="figure@24.[219,1358,193,1672]" captionTargetId-2="figure@25.[214,1406,187,1859]" captionTargetPageId-0="23" captionTargetPageId-1="24" captionTargetPageId-2="25" captionText-0="FIGURE 18. Dorsal view of the 10 th tergite of males Peropyrrhicia" captionText-1="FIGURE 19. Lateral view of the 10 th tergite of males Peropyrrhicia." captionText-2="FIGURE 20. Posterior view of the 10 th tergite of males Peropyrrhicia" captionText-3="FIGURE 21. Ventral view of the 10 th tergite of males Peropyrrhicia." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/165646/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/165647/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/165648/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Figures 18–21</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEB36D7FB74FF80C4ACF83FFE9FD7AB" blockId="21.[151,1437,1636,2035]" lastBlockId="22.[151,1437,151,285]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Female. Same characters of the male, with the following differences. Pronotum not saddle-shaped, tegmina very reduced, lateral and not overlapped, not exceeding the 1st tergite, their apical external angle about 45°, rounded (
<figureCitation id="136F2A52FB77FF80C4F5FF1BFEFAD7E3" box="[158,272,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1574,1596]" captionText="FIGURE 16. Pronotum and tegmina of Peropyrrhicia maculata" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Figure 16</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor gently up-curved, with fine denticles at both upper and lower apices. Subgenital plate with a wide base, converging apically and ending with a wide concavity. At the center of the plate a longitudinal keel is present (
<figureCitation id="136F2A52FB77FF80C49DFF53FE82D7AB" box="[246,360,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1915,1937]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,337,1879]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[191,1399,337,1880]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 23. Ovipositor and subgenital plate of females Peropyrrhicia – continued" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/165650/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Figure 23</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
