<subSubSection id="C34E655CFB77FF81C4ACF973FC0FD64F" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BEB36D7FB77FF81C4ACF973FC0FD64F" blockId="22.[151,1436,1791,2035]" lastBlockId="23.[151,1437,151,285]" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis id="B920EAC5FB77FF80C4ACF973FEDED04B" bold="true" box="[199,308,1791,1816]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Remarks</emphasis>
. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC54B26FB77FF80C5B4F973FCCBD04B" author="Schulthess-Schindler" box="[479,801,1791,1816]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" refString="Schulthess-Schindler, A. (1898) Orthopteres du Pays des Somalis, recueillis par L. Robecchi-Bricchetti et par le Prince E. Rispoli en 1892 - 93. Annali del Museo civico di storia naturale di Genova, 39, 161 - 216." type="journal article" year="1898">Schulthess-Schindler (1898)</bibRefCitation>
, both male and female of 
<taxonomicName id="4C544D54FB77FF80C020F88DFB3AD04B" box="[1099,1232,1791,1816]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Peropyrrhicia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis id="B920EAC5FB77FF80C020F88DFB3AD04B" box="[1099,1232,1791,1816]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P. maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described by him were collected at Biddwara (5°10'05.34&quot;N 38°39'39.91&quot;E), during the last expedition of the Italian explorer Eugenio Ruspoli (Ruspoli was killed by an injured elephant on 
<date id="FFEA1017FB77FF80C700F8C7FBAED030" box="[875,1092,1862,1891]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="1893-12-04">4th December 1893</date>
). However, as already pointed out by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC54B26FB77FF80C482F8E3FE6DD0D4" author="Ragge" box="[233,391,1903,1927]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" refString="Ragge, D. R. (1980) A review of the African Phaneropterinae with open tympana (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Entomology, 40, 1 - 192." type="journal article" year="1980">Ragge (1980)</bibRefCitation>
, only the female was collected at Biddwara, while the male came from Jam Jam (= Djam- Djam) (not to be mistaken for Jem Jem or Djem Djem, 
<quantity id="4CAC9B32FB77FF80C76FF81EFCA1D0F8" box="[772,843,1938,1963]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="km" value="60.0">60 km</quantity>
west of Addis). Biddwara is located in the S Oromia region, whereas Jam Jam is ca. 30 Km west of Harenna Forest (Bale Mts). According to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC54B26FB77FF80C019F83BFAE0D09C" author="Ragge" box="[1138,1290,1975,1999]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" refString="Ragge, D. R. (1980) A review of the African Phaneropterinae with open tympana (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Entomology, 40, 1 - 192." type="journal article" year="1980">Ragge (1980)</bibRefCitation>
it is possible that the two specimens belong to different species. The female is related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C544D54FB77FF80C064F857FB7AD0A1" box="[1039,1168,2011,2034]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Peropyrrhicia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antinorii">
<emphasis id="B920EAC5FB77FF80C064F857FB7AD0A1" box="[1039,1168,2011,2034]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P. antinorii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C544D54FB77FF80C0A6F857FABED0A1" box="[1229,1364,2011,2034]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Dichopetala" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="massaiae">
<emphasis id="B920EAC5FB77FF80C0A6F857FABED0A1" box="[1229,1364,2011,2034]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P. massaiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which it may be separated by shorter wings; its ovipositor is gently curved like in the latter two species, but its denticles are bigger than in the previous species (
<figureCitation id="136F2A52FB76FF81C6D0FF30FCC6D787" box="[699,812,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1915,1937]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,337,1879]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[191,1399,337,1880]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 23. Ovipositor and subgenital plate of females Peropyrrhicia – continued" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/165650/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figure 23</figureCitation>
). However, new specimens collected at Bale Mountains NP, ca. 150 Km E of Biddwara, show that this species is quite widespread in Central-Southern Ethiopia, and both male and female described by Schulthess-Schindler are indeed 
<taxonomicName id="4C544D54FB76FF81C731FE89FC34D64E" box="[858,990,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Peropyrrhicia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis id="B920EAC5FB76FF81C731FE89FC34D64E" box="[858,990,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">P. maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
